cat > man_3_printf << 'EOF'
.TH _PRINTF 3 "April 2026" "Holberton School" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- custom formatted output conversion
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.PP
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf()
function produces output according to a
.I format
string. It writes output to
.BR stdout ,
the standard output stream.
.PP
The
.I format
string is composed of zero or more directives: ordinary characters (not
.BR % ),
which are copied unchanged to the output stream, and conversion
specifications, each of which results in fetching zero or more subsequent
arguments.
.SS Conversion Specifiers
.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.
.TP
.B %s
Prints a string of characters. If the argument is NULL, prints
.IR (null) .
.TP
.B %d
Prints a decimal integer.
.TP
.B %i
Prints an integer in base 10.
.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal
.B %
character.
.SH RETURN VALUE
On success,
.B _printf()
returns the number of characters printed (excluding the null byte used to end output to strings).
.PP
If
.I format
is NULL or ends with an unhandled
.BR % ,
.B \-1
is returned.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Print a character:
.PP
.RS
_printf("%c", 'A');
.RE
.PP
Print a string:
.PP
.RS
_printf("%s", "Hello, World");
.RE
.PP
Print an integer:
.PP
.RS
_printf("%d", 1024);
.RE
.PP
Print a percent sign:
.PP
.RS
_printf("100%%");
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3),
.BR write (2),
.BR stdarg (3)
.SH AUTHORS
Written by Holberton School students.
.SH BUGS
Does not handle flag characters, field width, precision, or length modifiers.
EOF
